'''St Michael and All Angels Church, Mottram''' stands on Warhill overlooking the village of [[Mottram in Longdendale]], [[Greater Manchester]], England ({{gbmapping|SJ997953}}).  The church is a Grade&nbsp;II* [[listed building]].<ref name=images>{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=212546 |title=Images of England: Church of St Michael and All Angels, War Hill |accessdate=19&nbsp;December 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]]}}</ref>  It is an active [[Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the [[diocese of Chester]], the archdeaconry of Macclesfield and the deanery of Mottram.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chester.anglican.org/churches.asp| title = Churches in the Diocese| accessdate = 4&nbsp;July 2009| publisher = [[Diocese of Chester]]}}</ref>

==History==

The earliest evidence of a church on the site is in 1225 when clergy attached to the church were witnesses to local documents.<ref name=church>{{citation  |url=http://www.mottramparish.org.uk/ |title=History of St. Michael & All Angels |accessdate=19&nbsp;December 2007 |publisher=The Parish of Mottram-in-Longdendale }}</ref>  There is a further reference to the church in a taxation document dated 1291.<ref name=richards>{{citation  | last =Richards | first =Raymond | title =Old Cheshire Churches | publisher =Batsford | date =1947 | location =London | pages =242&ndash;247}}</ref>  The present church dates from the end of the 15th century.  A major restoration took place in 1854&ndash;55 by E. H. Shellard, during which the nave roof was raised.<ref name=church/>

==Structure==

The church is built from local stone quarried from Tinsell-Norr<ref name=richards/> in [[Perpendicular Period|Perpendicular]] style.<ref name=images/>  The plan consists of a west tower, a five-bay nave with [[clerestory]], north and south aisles, a two-bay chancel and a south porch.  At the east end of each aisle is a chapel.<ref>{{citation  | last =Salter | first =Mark | title =The Old Parish Churches of Cheshire | publisher =Folly Publications | date =1995 | location =Malvern  | page =54 | isbn =1871731232 }}</ref>  The north chapel is known as the Hollingworth Chapel and the south chapel is the Staley Chapel.<ref name=richards/>  The tower is in four stages with angled [[buttress]]es, a three-light west window above which is a clock face and two-light belfry openings.  In one corner is a stair turret. At the top is a [[castellation|castellated]] [[parapet]] with [[crocket]]ed corner [[finial]]s.<ref name=images/> 

==Fittings and furniture==

The oldest item in the church is the barrel-shaped [[Norman architecture|Norman]] [[baptismal font|font]].  Above the chancel arch are painted panels containing the [[Ten Commandments]], the [[Lord's Prayer]] and [[Creed]], together with a painting of [[Moses]] and [[Aaron]].<ref>{{citation  |url=http://www.thornber.net/cheshire/htmlfiles/mottraminlong.html |title=A Scrapbook of Cheshire Antiquities: Mottram-in-Longdendale|accessdate=19&nbsp;December 2007 |last=Thornber |first=Craig  |date=10&nbsp;February 2006 |year= |month= }}   </ref>  The [[alabaster]] [[pulpit]] of 1885 is by H. Hems.<ref name=images/>  The brass chandelier is dated 1755.<ref name=richards/>  The stained glass windows include one by [[Charles Eamer Kempe|Kempe]] dated 1917.<ref name=church/>  

The Hollingworth Chapel is now used as an organ gallery.  The Staley Chapel contains two [[sandstone]] effigies which are thought to be those of Sir Ralph Staveley and his wife dating from the early 15th century.  Also in the chapel is a white [[marble]] monument to Reginald Bretland who died in 1703.<ref name=richards/>  The [[ring of bells|ring]] is of eight bells which were cast in 1910 by [[Taylors Eayre & Smith Ltd|John Taylor & Co]].<ref>{{citation  |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=mottram&Submit=++Go++&DoveID=MOTTRAM+IL |title= Mottram S Michael |accessdate=11&nbsp;August 2008 |publisher= [[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] }}</ref>  The [[parish register]]s date from 1559 for marriages and burials and from 1562 for baptisms.<ref name=richards/>

==External features==

In the churchyard is a [[sundial]] with a dial dated 1811. It consists of a stone shaft with a copper dial and a [[gnomon]].<ref>{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=212550 |title=Images of England: Sundial |accessdate=19&nbsp;December 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]]}}</ref>  It is listed Grade&nbsp;II.  Also listed Grade II are the gatepiers, railings, steps and walls of the churchyard.<ref>{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=212548 |title=Images of England: Gatepiers, railings, steps and walls |accessdate=19&nbsp;December 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]]}}</ref>  Near the church is a medieval cross which was restored in 1760 and again in 1897, the latter restoration being to celebrate the [[Diamond Jubilee|diamond jubilee]] of [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]].  The octagonal shaft stands on a stepped circular [[ashlar]] [[plinth]].  On its top is a cubical sundial with three copper faces.<ref>{{citation  | last =Pevsner | first =Nikolaus | authorlink =Nikolaus Pevsner | coauthors =[[Edward Hubbard]] | title =The Buildings of England: Cheshire |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]]| date =2003| origyear=1971| location =New Haven| page =283 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn =0 300 09588 0 }}</ref>  It is listed Grade&nbsp;II*.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=212547 |title=Images of England: Cross |accessdate=7&nbsp;January 2008 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] }}</ref>

